Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.39,0:00:26.56,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Perceiving the truth hidden behind the dying\Nmessage, which one will win the deduction competition?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.02,0:00:28.44,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Perceiving the one and only truth,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.57,0:00:30.02,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,With the body of a child and the brains of an adult,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.32,0:00:32.28,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,His name is: Detective Conan!
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.11,0:02:02.20,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hattori and Kazuha came to see us in order to\Ninvite us to the Koushien finals and to Takarazuka.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.00,0:02:08.71,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But once they found out that both were\Nhappening on the same day, the two started quarreling.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.96,0:02:15.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Therefore, we used the murder case that Uncle was\Nasked to help solve as a deduction competition to decide.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.33,0:02:21.54,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which One's Deduction Show\N(Part Two)
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.39,0:02:26.39,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kazuha...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.56,0:02:29.86,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What's wrong, Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.57,0:02:34.11,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,How can I possibly understand this weird dying message?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.82,0:02:40.99,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,At this rate, we'll lose the deduction\Ncompetition and we won't be able to go to Takarazuka.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.45,0:02:43.37,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,When I think about that, I feel so disappointed...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.08,0:02:44.79,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Competition?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.54,0:02:54.13,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Idiot. In deductions, there's no winning or\Nlosing, there's no being superior or inferior because...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.05,0:02:59.34,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,There is always just a single truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.77,0:03:02.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's how it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.85,0:03:06.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, Hattori.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.60,0:03:08.02,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You figured it out too, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.48,0:03:10.65,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The real meaning behind that dying message.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.90,0:03:12.57,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Nope, no idea.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.15,0:03:18.99,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The main thing is, why were only\Nthese four blocks stained with ink?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.37,0:03:21.95,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,These are photos, but if these were real blocks,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.08,0:03:26.50,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We could lift them up like this and see the\Ncharacters on the back and maybe figure something out.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.46,0:03:34.30,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, you can't see the backs of the\Nblocks from the back of the pictures can you?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.31,0:03:43.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,So that's it, this guy...
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.85,0:03:52.98,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, this murdered president looks like he spent a\Nlot of effort to get those ink stains onto the blocks.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.65,0:03:58.70,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Because with his hands tied behind his back, he had\Nto use his fingers to feel the letter wells on the blocks,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.03,0:04:01.91,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,In order to figure out which\Ncharacter to rub the ink on, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.29,0:04:07.62,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The characters on these blocks are all different,\Nand some even have pictures of animals on them.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.04,0:04:10.33,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If it were me, I'd get it wrong for sure!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.55,0:04:14.30,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If these were shogi pieces instead of building blocks,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.38,0:04:17.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Then figuring out the character on the back and\Nadding ink stains would be really simple, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.22,0:04:19.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kudou...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.01,0:04:21.76,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Figuring out the character on the back?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.93,0:04:26.35,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Idiot! If they were shogi pieces,\Nwouldn't it be more complicated?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.09,0:04:33.19,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We couldn't tell it the ink-stained character or the unstained one was the one the president had intended.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.69,0:04:34.98,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh, really?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.61,0:04:38.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right, even though there\Nwas a character stained with ink,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.99,0:04:42.99,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He might have just placed the\Nshogi piece in the ink spilled on floor.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.25,0:04:47.62,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Could it be? Those four blocks...
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.17,0:04:53.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,And so? Those four employees\Nwho discovered the president's corpse,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.67,0:04:55.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Do they have any motives for killing the president?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.09,0:04:57.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ah, right.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.28,0:05:00.02,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,First of is the accountant, Aikou Nao{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.45,0:05:05.32,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,She was president Tsujiya's ex-wife. They\Ndivorced because Aikou{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} had an affair.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.78,0:05:07.30,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,350)}Aikou Nao
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.78,0:05:07.30,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,350)}Tsujiya Toy Manufacturing Accountant
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.40,0:05:07.70,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,They were still in dispute over the\Nquestion of the consolation money.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.92,0:05:09.94,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,As for the salesman, Hasami Atsushi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r},
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.34,0:05:15.88,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,It seems the president said he would be fired\Nif this year's profits were lower than last year's.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.85,0:05:15.93,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,0)}Hasami Atsushi
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.85,0:05:15.93,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,0)}Tsujiya Toy Manufacturing Sales
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.05,0:05:19.59,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,350)}Nakagami Isao
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.05,0:05:19.59,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,350)}Tsujiya Toy Manufacturing Design
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.72,0:05:19.94,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,The president said the same thing\Nto the designer, Nakagami Isao{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.09,0:05:25.46,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,In addition, it seems he's had a big argument\Nwith the president over the design of a new toy.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.84,0:05:30.29,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,Next, the vice-president, Iwatomi\NHajime{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}, didn't have any disputes.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.21,0:05:30.05,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,0)}Iwatomi Hajime
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.21,0:05:30.05,Character Card,,0,0,0,,{\fade(350,0)}Tsujiya Toy Manufacturing Vice President
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.38,0:05:34.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But if the president were to die, then he\Nwould be the one to inherit the company.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.46,0:05:38.34,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,So all four people have their individual motives.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.34,0:05:42.97,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"A-U-E". "O-U-I".
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.31,0:05:43.89,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"I"?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.47,0:05:46.31,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Just like that! Hurry and solve it!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.73,0:05:52.11,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Even though the relationships between\Nthe president and his employees were so bad,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.19,0:05:54.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This company was able to keep going.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.61,0:05:59.07,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, that's probably why they frequently\Nmet up at vice-president Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}'s house,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.16,0:06:01.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,To drink and complain about the president.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:02.62,0:06:09.08,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,On the day of the incident, June 29th, three of them\Nspent the night at the vice-president's place drinking.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.29,0:06:14.34,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It wasn't until the four of them went to work the next\Nday, the 30th, that they discovered the president's body.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.63,0:06:19.38,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh, and also something else that may\Nnot have anything to do with the case.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:20.22,0:06:22.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,All four have strange collecting habits.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.22,0:06:24.51,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Strange collecting habits?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.81,0:06:28.02,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Aikou{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}, who is sensitive to cold,\Nhas collected over 50 pairs of gloves.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.19,0:06:31.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Supposedly when she goes fishing\Nshe always wears at least three pairs.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.44,0:06:35.40,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}, who likes to watch movies,\Nhas collected over 30 pairs of sunglasses.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.78,0:06:40.07,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He's even bought limited edition\Nsunglasses that were worn by famous actors.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.61,0:06:42.95,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Nakagami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}, who likes horse racing, collects hats.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.16,0:06:46.83,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Depending on the race, he picks a\Ndifferent lucky hat out of the forty he owns.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.58,0:06:51.92,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}, who often played golf with the\Npresident, has collected 30 pairs of white shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.00,0:06:56.67,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,All of them are name-brand golf shoes, and it\Nseems he polishes the entire collection once every week.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.63,0:07:01.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Incidentally, the murdered\Npresident Tsujiya was a unrivaled idol fanatic.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.93,0:07:04.39,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It looks like he collected lots of idol goods.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.64,0:07:09.39,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Now that you mention it, there are a lot of\Nthose idol goods in the president's room back there.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.40,0:07:15.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Look, there's even some on this desk\NPen stands with idol photos on them.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.65,0:07:17.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,True enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.86,0:07:22.03,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, Kudou, have you noticed?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.37,0:07:24.87,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, you mean how the things in\Nthe room feel strangely out of place?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.37,0:07:27.37,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,However, it's not just that.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.87,0:07:31.50,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, there's still one more that's bothering me.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.96,0:07:35.25,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Well then, I suppose this calendar\Nwas also bought by the president?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.50,0:07:39.26,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right, apparently the\Npresident particularly liked this calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.43,0:07:42.47,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He stored all the past months\Ninstead of throwing them away.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.68,0:07:47.31,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hattori.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.44,0:07:51.81,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Did you buy it? That novel.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.77,0:07:55.77,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, my mother bought it\Nfor me first thing this morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.11,0:07:58.36,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}, have you figured something out?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.03,0:07:59.90,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.41,0:08:04.87,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Sorry, Ran{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}, I can't talk right\Nnow. I think I'm just about to solve it!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.54,0:08:11.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What's going on? Calling us here at this hour...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.88,0:08:15.25,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Don't tell me that you're still suspecting us?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.46,0:08:16.59,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ah, you see...
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.80,0:08:20.55,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Didn't you say the criminal was\Nsome outsider looking for valuables?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.18,0:08:25.60,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Your picking on us because there aren't\Nany witnesses for our alibis, aren't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.93,0:08:29.27,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Well that can't be helped! I really went to the horse race!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.43,0:08:33.35,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I stayed watching the finals of\Nthe golf tournament until the end!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.69,0:08:37.28,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I was at home and watching the\Nthree videos I'd rented one after the other.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.53,0:08:40.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I went fishing - and by coincidence, I went on my own.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.45,0:08:44.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,In that case, who was it that first\Ndiscovered the president's body?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.62,0:08:45.78,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Who is this kid?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.99,0:08:49.70,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Er, well, anyway, could you please\Ndescribe the situation at that time?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.33,0:08:53.29,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I was the first to discover the body.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.46,0:08:59.34,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Just as I was about to sit down in my seat, I\Nsaw the president lying here and started shouting.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.88,0:09:04.80,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We heard the vice-president shouting and so we all\Nran over to look, and then we called 110 (emergency).
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.14,0:09:05.97,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.56,0:09:12.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh-yeah, was it always the president who\Ntore the months off of the calendar over there?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.40,0:09:16.90,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Of course! If we had done it and\Ntore it wrong, he would get angry at us.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.98,0:09:18.90,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It was always the president who tore the months off.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.00,0:09:22.66,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,And then, after that, he would store them\Naway in his room as if they were precious.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.91,0:09:26.87,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Say, the one who wrote the daily schedules on the\Ncalendar would have been the president himself, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.45,0:09:33.88,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yes, in fact the president had finally been able to\Nschedule next Sunday for us all to play golf together.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.17,0:09:36.29,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Who knew that such a tragedy would occur.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.34,0:09:39.76,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Anyway, we're going to go look for something.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.63,0:09:42.43,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You guys continue your questioning.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.89,0:09:53.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,All right, let's find it.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.35,0:09:54.15,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.06,0:09:57.94,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Why was the video camera placed\Nwhere the president couldn't see it?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.44,0:09:59.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The position in which he was tied up...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.53,0:10:02.36,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The strange out-of-place\Narrangement of the things on the desk...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.99,0:10:06.83,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,And the blood spurt on the shoulder\Nof the coat the culprit was wearing...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.58,0:10:10.00,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The strange collecting habits of the four suspects...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.29,0:10:13.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,And the dying message left by the president.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.13,0:10:17.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Exactly. Now if we can just find that thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.38,0:10:20.21,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This mystery will be solved in one shot.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.84,0:10:24.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What? One of the alibis has been confirmed?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.34,0:10:28.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yes, I just checked the recording at the TV station,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.43,0:10:30.93,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He was photographed, quite clearly.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.85,0:10:34.40,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kudou.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.36,0:10:39.15,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ran{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.81,0:10:43.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I've found it, the June calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.20,0:10:46.99,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Although it's very faint,\Nthere's a smear of blood remaining.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.70,0:10:48.66,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,There's no mistake.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.08,0:10:49.87,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The culprit is...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.08,0:10:51.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I've got it!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.54,0:10:57.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ran{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}, I know who the culprit is!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.47,0:11:05.43,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Really? You know who it is, Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.26,0:11:10.72,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Look, this is the dying message left\Nbehind by the murdered president, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.81,0:11:13.98,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, the four blocks where the "o", "mo",\N"chi", and "ya" characters are stained with ink.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.69,0:11:17.27,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This isn't some kind of bizarre code.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.40,0:11:20.99,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It tells us who the criminal is just like it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.36,0:11:22.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Just like it is?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.03,0:11:26.82,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I don't think any one of them looks particularly like a toy.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.08,0:11:28.74,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,No, it's a name.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:28.91,0:11:29.45,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Name?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.95,0:11:32.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,None of their four names are related to "o-mo-chi-ya."
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.33,0:11:35.37,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Remember, Heiji mentioned it earlier?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.46,0:11:38.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It might not be the characters\Nstained with ink he intended us to read.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.25,0:11:41.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He might have just put the blocks in the ink.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.59,0:11:47.05,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,In that case, the character on the back of the\None stained with ink contains the true message.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.10,0:11:50.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Even if that's so, you can't see the\Ncharacter on the back-from the photos.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.14,0:11:54.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Should I have forensics bring the four blocks here then?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.06,0:11:56.77,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We can work it out without doing that.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.98,0:12:00.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,For example, the ink stained block with the character "o".
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.36,0:12:04.28,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If we expand it of it, we get something like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.70,0:12:06.20,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"U-E-O."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.87,0:12:10.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You can easily guess which\Ncharacters go in the blank spaces.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.66,0:12:15.50,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, to be sure, I checked the remaining blocks\Nover there, and they were just like what I expected.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.58,0:12:21.59,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The each of the vowels "a-i-u-e-o" were\Nplaced in the same order on all of the blocks.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.76,0:12:23.47,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right, isn't it?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.93,0:12:31.02,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Correct, the 50 Japanese syllables, 5 to a column plus 1\Nanimal, meant that we had six sides to make a cube with.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.35,0:12:32.52,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yep, yep.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.81,0:12:39.52,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,After you've understood where the characters are\Nplaced on the six faces of the blocks, the rest is easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.11,0:12:41.98,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,On the opposite side of the ink stained "o" is the letter "i".
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.33,0:12:43.70,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Opposite "mo" is "mi".
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.95,0:12:46.20,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Opposite "chi" is "to". See how it goes?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.82,0:12:52.41,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I get it! So the real dying\Nmessage was "i-mi-to" and one more...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.58,0:12:53.75,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Isn't this strange?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.33,0:13:01.34,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r} is correct, on the fourth block,\Nbelow the "ya" character should be "yu", but it says "yo".
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.80,0:13:04.76,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It's because that block is special.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.13,0:13:08.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Look, on the right of the "yo" the character "wo"\Nfrom the syllable line "wa-wo-n" is written, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.97,0:13:14.18,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which means that this block is actually\Na combined line of "ya-yu-yo-wa-wo-n."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.85,0:13:17.44,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If you put characters onto the\Nblock using the order I described before,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.44,0:13:20.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Using the character "n" in the\Nplace of the animal finishes it off.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.32,0:13:24.78,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,In this case, the character opposite\Nthe ink stained "ya", is the character "wa".
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.36,0:13:29.53,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which means the dying message\Nbecomes "i-mi-to-wa" doesn't it?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.12,0:13:32.12,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which means...
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.12,0:13:33.29,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"I-M-I-WA-TO."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.66,0:13:34.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"I-WA-MI-TO."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.17,0:13:36.67,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,"I-WA-TO..."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.67,0:13:41.59,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right! What the president intended\Nto leave behind before he was killed was...
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.67,0:13:47.01,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You name, vice-president Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.89,0:13:53.14,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,So that's how it is? You killed the president\Nso that you could have the company for yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.14,0:13:54.48,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,No, no, it wasn't me!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.81,0:13:58.69,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's amazing, Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}! You\Nsolved the case before Hattori{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-kun{\r}!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.69,0:14:01.11,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yep, we've won the deduction competition!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.15,0:14:02.40,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That means we...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:02.53,0:14:04.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Can go see Takaruzuka!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.70,0:14:09.20,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I'm sorry, Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-kun{\r}, but Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} is not the culprit.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.91,0:14:13.45,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Chiba{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-kun{\r} called me earlier...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.00,0:14:16.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The time of the crime was about\N5 PM on the 29th of last month.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.50,0:14:19.92,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} was shown on television at that time.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.38,0:14:20.88,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,No way!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.88,0:14:21.92,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,How is that possible?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.01,0:14:24.42,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You might ask me, "How is\Nthat possible?" but it's the truth.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.76,0:14:26.01,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Don't tell me you have a twin?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.34,0:14:27.18,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,No, I don't!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.68,0:14:34.81,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which means, I'm sorry to say,\NKazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-kun{\r}'s reasoning just now was incorrect.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.81,0:14:35.60,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh no.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.69,0:14:38.31,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,No, She wasn't wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.57,0:14:47.49,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The four blocks spelling out "lwatomi" was the actual\Ndying message left by the president before he was killed.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.95,0:14:48.57,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Heiji.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.20,0:14:52.83,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, Hattori{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-kun{\r}, Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} has an alibi...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.83,0:14:57.04,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which isn't surprising, seeing\Nas Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} wasn't the culprit.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.58,0:15:03.30,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Huh? Didn't you just say that\N"lwatomi" was the actual dying message?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.76,0:15:09.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right, I did say that, but I never\Nsaid that it was the "correct" dying message.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.18,0:15:12.35,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, hey. What are you talking about?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.81,0:15:18.56,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Haven't I said? The situation when the president used\Nthe blocks to leave behind that message, think back to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.98,0:15:24.15,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Well, let's see. The president was lying\Nbeside the desk with his hands tied behind him.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.69,0:15:30.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He picked up the blocks beside him and\Nstained them in the ink splattered on the floor.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.66,0:15:34.58,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right, it's the ink splattered on\Nthe floor behind him that's the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.33,0:15:36.79,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What's the problem with it?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.04,0:15:40.88,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This ink was probably spilled when the\Npresident was struggling with the culprit.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.46,0:15:44.01,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ah, that's what I thought at first.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.47,0:15:47.22,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But then I noticed how the things on\Nthe desk look strangely out-of-place.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.72,0:15:50.01,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Out of place?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.39,0:16:00.86,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What's this? Isn't that strange? I just bumped\Nthe desk lightly and the pen stand toppled over.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.11,0:16:06.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Because, wasn't it during the struggle with the\Nculprit that the desk was struck and the ink spilled?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.91,0:16:10.78,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Why didn't the pen stand fall over at that time too?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.99,0:16:12.62,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Now that you mention it...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.99,0:16:14.66,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It seems like...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.75,0:16:18.62,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The culprit deliberately spilled the ink, doesn't it?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.17,0:16:22.50,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Idiot! Why would the culprit do something like that?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.92,0:16:27.01,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Wouldn't the victim write something\Nthat lead back to such a inept criminal...
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.26,0:16:28.97,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Maybe.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.34,0:16:30.93,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Could it have been deliberate?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.01,0:16:36.10,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's right. The culprit deliberately\Nspilt the ink to allow the president to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.56,0:16:39.27,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Leave behind a dying\Nmessage saying who the culprit was.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.61,0:16:43.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, in that case, wouldn't he be\Nimmediately revealed as the culprit.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.69,0:16:47.07,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It would only reveal who the culprit was\Nif the president had seen the culprit's face.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.40,0:16:51.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Now, how about lying down on the\Nfloor like the tied-up president was?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.08,0:16:58.75,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You understand what the\Npresident was feeling at the time, don't you?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.72,0:17:08.88,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's it, shoes! Shoes!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.34,0:17:12.26,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The culprit used this desk to block the president's view,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.39,0:17:15.10,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,So he could only decide who the culprit was by his shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.48,0:17:18.94,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Which means that the culprit\Nput on Iwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}'s white shoes
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.94,0:17:22.40,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,To deliberately make the\Npresident leave that dying message.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.15,0:17:28.15,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That the video camera was placed where the\Ntied-up president couldn't see it is the proof.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.99,0:17:35.58,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He observed the president on the monitor, and\Nthen killed him after he left his dying message.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.75,0:17:38.12,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But who could have done it?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.67,0:17:39.96,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, Uncle!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.13,0:17:45.05,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I found a strange calendar in the president's room. See!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.09,0:17:49.47,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I think you might be able to work out something from it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.14,0:17:54.22,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hmm, there's seems to be a slight\Nstain, but nothing else is suspicious.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.35,0:17:56.47,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What? You still don't get it?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.35,0:18:00.81,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This stain was left behind after\Nwiping off the blood from the calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.90,0:18:04.44,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Also, don't you think it's strange?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.61,0:18:11.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The president was killed on June 29th,\Nyet the calendar in this room is for July?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.70,0:18:16.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The daily schedule for the 30th is\Nstill written on the ripped off calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.79,0:18:21.00,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We should assume that the\Nculprit tore it off for some reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:21.38,0:18:22.50,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, hey, hey!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.63,0:18:27.13,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I figure the reason for tearing it off was\Nto hide the blood that had wiped off on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.13,0:18:31.59,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Wasn't there a place that looked as if\Nblood stains there had been wiped off?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:31.80,0:18:36.81,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ah! The coat the culprit was wearing had\Nwiped-off blood stains on the left shoulder!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.27,0:18:41.31,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Well then, let's have the four of\Nthem line up in front of the calendar.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.81,0:18:42.77,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.36,0:18:46.28,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The one who could get blood from\Ntheir shoulder on the top of the calendar...
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.57,0:18:47.57,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Ah, idiot!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.40,0:18:53.49,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You are the only person tall enough to do it, Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.33,0:18:55.49,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He said it...
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.00,0:19:01.67,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,When the president returned here, Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}\Nbeat him unconscious from the back with a golf club.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.13,0:19:05.09,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He came to and was leaving the mistaken dying message,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.46,0:19:09.93,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} watched him on video camera,\Nwhile wearing Mr. Iwatomi's shoes, of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.76,0:19:13.30,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Now the reason why the blood\Non his coat got onto the calendar,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.43,0:19:17.43,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Is because he leaned against the wall in\Nrelief after being the president to death.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.06,0:19:25.36,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The reason Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} didn't tear off the calendar\Nwas because he only noticed the blood on it the next day.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.82,0:19:30.20,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Incidentally, secretly taking\Nlwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}'s white shoes was an easy task.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.78,0:19:36.04,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Apparently the employees often get together at\Nlwatomi{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r}'s house, so there were plenty of chances.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.50,0:19:41.42,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, just the blood on the calendar isn't\Nenough evidence to prove that Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} did it.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.75,0:19:43.83,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Nope, the evidence is the shoes.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.55,0:19:50.13,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,While Hasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} waited for the president to leave\Nhis message, he was wearing them the whole time.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.51,0:19:52.39,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,This left a definite scent.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.97,0:19:55.76,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Let the police dogs have a\Nsniff and you'll know soon enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.22,0:20:02.35,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Still, since it was a risk to leave his scent in the shoes,\NHasami{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-san{\r} must have had some other important reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.06,0:20:05.61,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Why don't you explain to us?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.53,0:20:10.32,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I wanted the vice president to be\Naccused of the president's murder.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.70,0:20:15.33,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,So that he would be forced out of\Nthe toy production process. That's all.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.74,0:20:19.45,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Why? I can't think why you would bear a grudge.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.66,0:20:23.17,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I don't bear a grudge, the children do.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.75,0:20:29.21,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The children that bought this\Nbatch of toys you and the president sold.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.80,0:20:31.26,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,W-What do you mean?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.18,0:20:35.89,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Look, for example, these blocks. See\Nhow the corners have been smoothed off.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.39,0:20:41.27,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,To reduce costs, the president and vice-president\Nsaid that it would be easier not to smooth off the corners.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.77,0:20:43.90,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Not just the blocks, but the other toys too.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.36,0:20:47.07,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It's true that at first glance they look\Nfine, and have been selling well too.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.19,0:20:49.28,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But they could injure the children who buy them.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.61,0:20:52.91,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I opposed the idea at first, but I\Nwas told that if I did I would be fired.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.45,0:20:55.33,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But that's no reason to go so far!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.87,0:20:57.49,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The company is having hard times, you know.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.16,0:20:59.12,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hard times?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.12,0:21:03.67,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Guess what the president said when he was tied up.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.50,0:21:07.92,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Hey, Iwatomi Are you doing this for money?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.01,0:21:11.42,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If you think there's no money,\Nyou're wrong! Just look in the vault!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.51,0:21:13.68,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,We had money?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.68,0:21:17.39,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yes, although I don't know who or\Nhow they cheated in order to save it.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.93,0:21:23.85,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,But, regardless, I couldn't let them sell\Nthose badly-made toys to unsuspecting children.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.78,0:21:40.41,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,When I realized it, I had to that nostalgic river side
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.29,0:21:50.17,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Envisioning the sequel the dream I had yesterday
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.51,0:21:56.89,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh that day you seemed so grown-up
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.14,0:22:02.89,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Unable to even say goodbye, I hid under my umbrella
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.35,0:22:08.69,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,If we cross paths again... Oh please
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.03,0:22:12.36,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That time, forget-me-not
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.53,0:22:22.21,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Not like love, not like loving, not something that's changing
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.79,0:22:33.22,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It's only you I like, and that's how I think it will always be
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.64,0:22:42.98,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Holding onto my aimless feelings, I look back as people often do
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.40,0:22:55.70,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Stopping the scene were we chanced to meet from fading gently away
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.37,0:22:58.79,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You know, you understood that trick really well.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.25,0:23:00.54,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It's thanks to a novel.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.96,0:23:07.25,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,Novel Title: The Last Will and Testament Prepared by a Devil
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.96,0:23:07.25,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,The title of the novel my mother bought\Nfor me this morning helped me work it out.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.30,0:23:10.38,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You'll really have to thank your mother then.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.67,0:23:13.26,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Because of her you've also\Nwon the deduction competition.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:13.43,0:23:15.64,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, I guess it's Koushien...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:15.93,0:23:17.05,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Congratulations, Heiji.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.39,0:23:19.22,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Oh no. I accidentally won.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.64,0:23:23.69,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,Translator's Note: Rokkou Oroshi (The Wind From Mt. Rokkou)\Nis the fight song for the Hanshin Tigers, Osaka's baseball team.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.64,0:23:23.69,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,I guess I'll just have to practice the "Rokkou Oroshi" then.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.02,0:23:26.36,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,W-Wait a second, Kazuha.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.36,0:23:31.03,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Kazuha{\rHonorifics - Dialogue}-chan{\r}, would you like me to ask\NHattori if he'll consider going to Takarazuka?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.74,0:23:34.24,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,You did solve the dying message, after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.70,0:23:36.95,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's half of the work.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.95,0:23:37.91,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It's no use.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.95,0:23:43.46,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Besides, what I really wanted to\Nsee wasn't Takarazuka or Koushien...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.04,0:23:50.13,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,It was the shinning look on Heiji's\Nface when he finally solved the case.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.76,0:23:55.55,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That's strange, where did I screw up?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.30,0:23:58.35,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Dumb-ass.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.47,0:24:03.48,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Wow! It's Koushien!
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.40,0:24:11.74,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,What the heck is that? He\Nshould come here and get it himself.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.03,0:24:15.78,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,That can only mean he doesn't care\Nif we trace it back to him later, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.03,0:24:21.12,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Yeah, if we can't find him by the\Nend of the game, he'll kill himself.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.66,0:24:23.79,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,He could still be there!
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.70,0:24:29.54,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Next Conan Special: The Miracle at Koushien Ball Park\NThe Defiants Face The Dark Demon
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.89,0:24:32.88,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Next Conan's Hint
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.05,0:24:34.59,Dialogue,,0,0,0,,Retried uniform number
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.11,0:24:37.11,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,Next time it's a two hour special Christmas present.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.16,0:24:38.85,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,With Koushien as the stage, I play the lead!
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.85,0:24:40.85,Dialogue Top,,0,0,0,,Eh? Hang on...
